# TOP — directory-scoped ownership
#
# Per ADR-0017. Every directory in the repository has an owner.
# Pull requests modifying files in a directory require approval from at
# least one of that directory's owners. Cross-cutting changes (touching
# Core + one or more workflow extensions) require approval from each
# affected owner.
#
# Today the convener (@bo-lora) is the only steward; every owner entry
# resolves to that GitHub user. As working groups form, the relevant
# directory's owner is reassigned to the GitHub team representing that
# working group (e.g., `@scientixai/clinical-research-wg`). The history
# of who owned what is queryable through git blame on this file.

# === Default owner (catch-all) ===

*                                       @bo-lora


# === Project-level documents ===

/README.md                              @bo-lora
/CONTRIBUTING.md                        @bo-lora
/LICENSE                                @bo-lora
/CNAME                                  @bo-lora

/first-principles.md                    @bo-lora
/first-principles.html                  @bo-lora
/manifesto.html                         @bo-lora
/roadmap.md                             @bo-lora
/roadmap.html                           @bo-lora
/taxonomy.md                            @bo-lora

/index.html                             @bo-lora
/images/                                @bo-lora


# === Core — load-bearing universal layer ===
# Changes to Core require Core-steward approval. Cross-WG impact —
# every workflow extension imports Core, so Core changes ripple.

/core/                                  @bo-lora
/taxonomy/                              @bo-lora


# === Governance — process and decisions ===
# Changes to governance affect every WG. Owned by the conveners.

/governance/                            @bo-lora
/.github/                               @bo-lora


# === Workflow extensions ===
# Each workflow's directory is owned by its working group. The WG owns
# the spec, the SKOS/OWL/SHACL artifacts, the worked examples, and the
# documentation under its directory. Cross-references INTO the workflow
# from other workflows are not WG-owned (those edges are negotiated).

/clinical-research/                     @bo-lora
